                                               Logging, Metrics & Automation (Simplified)
     “Logging, metrics, and automation together form the foundation of observability and scalability in modern distributed systems.”
 Why this matters
Small systems → can survive without much monitoring
Large-scale systems → impossible to manage without it

 As systems grow:

More servers
More users
More failures

You need visibility + control

1. LOGGING

Definition

Logging = recording events/errors happening inside the system

 Your notes explained:
Monitoring error logs
→ Track failures, exceptions, crashes
Per server level
→ Each server generates its own logs
Centralized logging
→ Combine all logs into one place
 Real-world tools:
ELK Stack (Elasticsearch + Logstash + Kibana)
New Relic
Splunk

2. METRICS
Definition

Metrics = numerical data about system performance

 Types (from your notes)
1️⃣ Host-level metrics
CPU usage
Memory usage
Disk I/O

 “Is my server healthy?”

2️⃣ Aggregated metrics
DB performance
Cache hit rate
API latency

 “Is my system efficient?”

Business metrics
Daily Active Users (DAU)
Revenue
Conversions

 “Is my business growing?”

 Tools:
Grafana
Prometheus
Datadog
 Example
CPU = 95% 
→ Server overloaded
→ Scale system

3. AUTOMATION
Definition

Automation = using tools to perform tasks automatically

📌 From your notes:
✔ When needed
When system becomes big & complex
✔ Continuous Integration (CI)
Code is automatically:
Built
Tested
Verified

👉 Every commit is checked

✔ Automating:
Builds
Testing
Deployment
🧩 Tools:
Jenkins
GitHub Actions
GitLab CI/CD
💡 Example

Developer pushes code →

Tests run automatically
Build created
Deployed to server
